SIMPLE: whisper
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Whisper
<hw>Whis"per</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Whispered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Whispering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS.
<ets>hwisprian</ets>; akin to G. <ets>wispern</ets>, <ets>wispeln</ets>,
OHG. <ets>hwispal<?/n</ets>, Icel. <ets>hv⟦imac⟧skra</ets>, Sw.
<ets>hviska</ets>, Dan. <ets>hviske</ets>; of imitative origin. Cf.
<er>Whistle</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To speak softly, or under the breath, so as to be
heard only by one near at hand; to utter words without sonant breath; to
talk without that vibration in the larynx which gives sonorous, or
vocal, sound. See <er>Whisper</er>, <pos>n.</pos></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To make a low, sibilant sound or noise.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The hollow, <qex>whispering</qex> breeze.</q>
<rj><qau>Thomson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To speak with suspicion, or timorous caution; to
converse in whispers, as in secret plotting.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All that hate me <qex>whisper</qex> together against me.</q>
<rj><qau>Ps. xli. 7.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Whisper</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Whisper
<hw>Whis"per</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To utter in a low and nonvocal tone; to say under
the breath; hence, to mention privately and confidentially, or in a
whisper.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They might buzz and <qex>whisper</qex> it one to another.</q>
<rj><qau>Bentley.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To address in a whisper, or low voice.</def>
<mark>[Archaic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And <qex>whisper</qex> one another in the ear.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Where gentlest breezes <qex>whisper</qex> souls distressed.</q>
<rj><qau>Keble.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To prompt secretly or cautiously; to inform
privately.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧He came to
<xex>whisper</xex> Wolsey.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Whisper</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Whisper
<hw>Whis"per</hw>, <pos>n.</pos>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A low, soft, sibilant voice or utterance, which can
be heard only by those near at hand; voice or utterance that employs
only breath sound without tone, friction against the edges of the vocal
cords and arytenoid cartilages taking the place of the vibration of the
cords that produces tone; sometimes, in a limited sense, the sound
produced by such friction as distinguished from <xex>breath sound</xex>
made by friction against parts of the mouth. See <er>Voice</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>, 2, and <xex>Guide to Pronunciation</xex>, ⟦sect⟧⟦sect⟧ 5,
153, 154.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The inward voice or <qex>whisper</qex> can not give a tone.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Soft <qex>whispers</qex> through the assembly went.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A cautious or timorous speech.</def>
<rj><au>South.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Something communicated in secret or by whispering; a
suggestion or insinuation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A low, sibilant sound.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The
<xex>whispers</xex> of the leaves.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Tennyson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Whisperer</ent>⟦br⟧
